## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical data processing in JavaScript: time-window filtering, per-user aggregation, and deterministic tie-breaking.

## Key Concepts
- Time-window filtering
- Hash map for counts
- Stable sorting with tie-breakers
- Input validation and edge cases

## Code Example

```javascript
function topUsers(events) {
  const now = Date.now();
  const window = 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;
  const counts = new Map();
  for (const e of events) {
    const t = Date.parse(e.ts);
    if (Number.isNaN(t)) continue;
    if (now - t <= window) {
      counts.set(e.userId, (counts.get(e.userId) || 0) + 1);
    }
  }
  const arr = Array.from(counts.entries());
  arr.sort((a, b) => b[1] - a[1] || a[0].localeCompare(b[0]));
  return arr.slice(0, 3).map(([id]) => id);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt this for streaming data?
- How would you test with synthetic data to cover edge cases?
